      <front>
         <div1 type="abstract" n="1">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <abbr>ALS</abbr>
                  <extent>4 pp.</extent>
                  <date value="1859-01-08">08 01 1859</date>
                  <idno rend="suppress">SPEC.MMS.138_3</idno>
                  <title>Letter from Sophia Peabody Hawthorne to 
Elizabeth Palmer Peabody</title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p> Sophia and family are in Rome recovering from sickness.  The family plans to stay in Rome for February, March, and half of April.  From there the famly will travel to Venice, northern Italian cities, Geneva, and Paris.  Sophia informs Elizabeth on the status of her friends in Italy.</p>
         </div1>
      </front>
      <body>
         <div1 type="letter" n="1">
            <head>Letter from Sophia Peabody Hawthorne to 
Elizabeth Palmer Peabody - January 8th, 1859</head>

<!-- Page 1 -->
<pb mmid="/1/196aae78-c619-4c1d-af07-e32c2f35e5d4" n="1"/>

            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place">Rome</name>.
<date value="1859-01-08">January 8th 1859</date>
               </dateline>
               
<lb/><add hand="Unknown" place="centered below dateline">Mrs H</add>
<lb id="L03001" n="001"/>
               <salute>My dear <name type="Recipient">Elizabeth</name>,
                 <seg>
                     <note target="n1">1</note>
                  </seg>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p id="L003P01" n="1">I am really

<lb id="L03L002" n="002"/>too tired to write a letter,
<lb id="L03L003" n="003"/>but cannot bear to let a
<lb id="L03L004" n="004"/>chance slip. <name type="person">Una</name>
               <seg>
                  <note target="n2">2</note>
               </seg>
	has

<lb id="L03L005" n="005"/>written a sad letter which
<lb id="L03L006" n="006"/>I fear will make your
<lb id="L03L007" n="007"/>heart ache. I am glad
<lb id="L03L008" n="008"/>to say that the Roman
<lb id="L03L009" n="009"/>fever seems to have been
<lb id="L03L010" n="010"/>arrested in her &mdash;; for she
<lb id="L03L011" n="011"/>has had no chills for two
<lb id="L03L012" n="012"/>days. She is a lily now,
<lb id="L03L013" n="013"/>her lifelong roses snatched
<lb id="L03L014" n="014"/>away, but during these
<lb id="L03L015" n="015"/>two days I have thought
<lb id="L03L016" n="016"/>to see a dawn of roses
<lb id="L03L017" n="017"/>in her cheeks and lips,
<lb id="L03L018" n="018"/>though she is now suffering
<lb id="L03L019" n="019"/>from influenza.</p>

<p n="2" id="L003P02">
    
<lb id="L03L020" n="020"/>
               <name type="person">Ada's</name>
               <seg>
                  <note target="n3">3</note>
               </seg>
	fever is past. She

<lb id="L03L021" n="021"/>is well of that today, but has
<lb id="L03L022" n="022"/>a very painful shoulder &mdash;;
<lb id="L03L023" n="023"/>and lies in bed still.

<!-- Page 2 -->
<pb mmid="/5/51bc2458-2f58-442d-b224-5525a57d8ce6" n="2"/>
               
<lb id="L03L024" n="024"/> I have had no moment to 
<lb id="L03L025" n="025"/> write to you in all these 
<lb id="L03L026" n="026"/> weeks &mdash;; having been ill 
<lb id="L03L027" n="027"/> myself in the interval 
<lb id="L03L028" n="028"/> of nursing others.  No Rome 
<lb id="L03L029" n="029"/> this winter for us so far. 
<lb id="L03L030" n="030"/> My journal is left in the 
<lb id="L03L031" n="031"/> middle of a sentence, which 
<lb id="L03L032" n="032"/> can never be recalled 
<lb id="L03L033" n="033"/> now, <del type="overstrike" hand="SPH">though,</del> and I am 
<lb id="L03L034" n="034"/> sorry, because I had an 
<lb id="L03L035" n="035"/> idea of the <unclear rend="" reason="could be either Faun or 
Fauna" resp="" cert="" hand="SPH">Faun</unclear> at that moment. </p>

<p id="L0303" n="3">
               
<lb id="L03L036" n="036"/> Perhaps we shall have 
<lb id="L03L037" n="037"/> February and March 
<lb id="L03L038" n="038"/> for a little enjoyment 
<lb id="L03L039" n="039"/> of Rome, and half of April. 
<lb id="L03L040" n="040"/> Then we leave it for aye 
<lb id="L03L041" n="041"/> and go to Venice and thence 
<lb id="L03L042" n="042"/> to the cities in the north 
<lb id="L03L043" n="043"/> of Italy &amp; to Geneva and 
<lb id="L03L044" n="044"/> Paris. </p>
            <p id="L0304" n="4">
               
<lb id="L03L045" n="045"/>
               <name type="person">Mrs. Ward</name>
               <seg>
                  <note target="n4">4</note>
               </seg> is here and I 
               
<lb id="L03L046" n="046"/> have not had a moment 
<lb id="L03L047" n="047"/> to go and see her.  But I had 
<lb id="L03L048" n="048"/> a long note from her. She

<!-- Page 3 -->
<pb mmid="/e/e3971fc5-3142-4469-ab62-6adca0de01cd" n="3"/>
               
<lb id="L03L049" n="049"/> is very happy and content in her 
<lb id="L03L050" n="050"/> sunny sky-parlor in the Hotel 
<lb id="L03L051" n="051"/> d'Angliterre &mdash; <q>with no cares, no 
<lb id="L03L052" n="052"/> anxieties, only hopes</q> she says. 
<lb id="L03L053" n="053"/> She suffered terribly from the 
<lb id="L03L054" n="054"/> severe treatment of <name type="person">Dr Simpson</name>
<lb id="L03L055" n="055"/> but expects to feel benefit 
<lb id="L03L056" n="056"/> next summer from it. 
<lb id="L03L057" n="057"/> Neither have I been able to see 
<lb id="L03L058" n="058"/> once <name type="person">Mrs Browning</name>
               <seg>
                  <note target="n5">5</note>
               </seg>, and 
               
<lb id="L03L059" n="059"/> only once <name type="person">Mr Browning</name>
               <seg>
                  <note target="n6">6</note>
               </seg>who 
               
<lb id="L03L060" n="060"/> has been three times to see 
<lb id="L03L061" n="061"/> us.  Mrs Browning does not 
<lb id="L03L062" n="062"/> make visits. <name type="person">Mary Motley</name>
               <seg>
                  <note target="n7">7</note>
               </seg>
               
<lb id="L03L063" n="063"/> I see here sometimes.  I 
<lb id="L03L064" n="064"/> have read the Dutch Republic <seg>
                  <note target="n8">8</note>
               </seg>
               
<lb id="L03L065" n="065"/> during my watches, and the 
<lb id="L03L066" n="066"/> book is superb, I think. 
<lb id="L03L067" n="067"/>
               <name type="person">Miss Cushman</name>
               <seg>
                  <note target="n9">9</note>
               </seg> has been here, 
               
<lb id="L03L068" n="068"/> but I could not see her. 
<lb id="L03L069" n="069"/> <name type="person">Mr. Hawthorne</name> saw her. 
<lb id="L03L070" n="070"/> No society for me this winter. 
<lb id="L03L071" n="071"/><rs id="RHL" reg="Hawthorne, Rose">Rosebud</rs> is exquisitely good 
<lb id="L03L072" n="072"/> generous and considerate in 
<lb id="L03L073" n="073"/> these times, but I can give 
<lb id="L03L074" n="074"/> you no Altar of Roses now. 
<lb id="L03L075" n="075"/> <name type="person">Mr. Hawthorne</name> is quite 
<lb id="L03L076" n="076"/> well.  Here is cause for 
<lb id="L03L077" n="077"/> great joy &mdash; for last winter he 

<!-- Page 4 -->
<pb mmid="/c/ca08174b-ea5d-450a-8de1-35f29885e224" n="4"/>
               
<lb id="L03L0O78" n="078"/> had the Grippe three months. 
<lb id="L03L079" n="079"/> <name type="person">Julian</name>
               <seg>
                  <note target="n10">10</note>
               </seg> also is well with 
               
<lb id="L03L080" n="080"/> only slight nose cold. 
<lb id="L03L081" n="081"/> <name type="person">Rose</name>
               <seg>
                  <note target="n11">11</note>
               </seg> has today gone to 
               
<lb id="L03L082" n="082"/> the Palazzo Galitzin <seg>
                  <note target="n12">12</note>
               </seg> to see 
<lb id="L03L083" n="083"/><name type="person">the Westons</name>, who delight in 
<lb id="L03L084" n="084"/> her.  She draws with a 
<lb id="L03L085" n="085"/> wonderful expression. 
<lb id="L03L086" n="086"/> Julian copies <name type="person">Flaxman</name>
               <seg>
                  <note target="n13">13</note>
               </seg>
               
<lb id="L03L087" n="087"/><foreign lang="FR">a merveille.</foreign></p>

<p id="L0305" n="5">
               
<lb id="L03L088" n="088"/> I long to answer all 
<lb id="L03L089" n="089"/> your letters one by one &mdash; 
<lb id="L03L090" n="090"/> and I long to tell you much. 
<lb id="L03L091" n="091"/> I have sent some letters 
<lb id="L03L092" n="092"/> of Una to you and Mary 
<lb id="L03L093" n="093"/> lately.  I never got 
<lb id="L03L094" n="094"/> yours and Mary's letters 
<lb id="L03L095" n="095"/> directed to Florence.  Though 
<lb id="L03L096" n="096"/> Mr. Browning has written 
<lb id="L03L097" n="097"/> about <del type="overwritten" cert="unclear">?</del>them to the Post Office 
<lb id="L03L098" n="098"/> they do not come.  I have 
<lb id="L03L099" n="099"/> lost all your account of dear 
<lb id="L03L100" n="100"/> <name type="person">Dr. Wesselhoeft</name>. <seg>
                  <note target="n14">14</note>
               </seg> I endure 
<lb id="L03L101" n="101"/> astonishingly through all 
<lb id="L03L102" n="102"/> things.  Goodbye with 
<lb id="L03L103" n="103"/> thousand blessings<unclear>.</unclear> </p>
            <closer> Yours ever 
<lb/>
               <signed>
                  <name type="sender">Sophia</name>
               </signed>
            </closer>
         </div1>
      </body>
